Hello, this is 6-minute English from BBCLearningEnglish.

4
00:00:11.000 --> 00:00:12.000
I'm Phil.

5
00:00:12.000 --> 00:00:13.000
And I'm Beth.

6
00:00:13.000 --> 00:00:17.000
Nowadays, I often see people carrying water bottles with them

7
00:00:17.000 --> 00:00:19.000
to make sure they drink enough.

8
00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:22.000
How much water do you drink a day, Phil?

9
00:00:22.000 --> 00:00:23.000
Oh, I don't know.

10
00:00:23.000 --> 00:00:26.000
Um, maybe about a liter.

11
00:00:26.000 --> 00:00:29.000
Okay, and do you know how much water you should drink

12
00:00:29.000 --> 00:00:30.000
a day?

13
00:00:30.000 --> 00:00:33.000
I think it's probably about two liters.

14
00:00:33.000 --> 00:00:38.000
Ah, well, the number many people have heard is two liters a day.

15
00:00:38.000 --> 00:00:42.000
Of course, everyone needs to drink some water.

16
00:00:42.000 --> 00:00:45.000
Over half the human body is made up of it.

17
00:00:45.000 --> 00:00:49.000
But exactly how much water do we need to stay healthy.

18
00:00:49.000 --> 00:00:53.000
That's what we'll be discussing in this program along with some useful

19
00:00:53.000 --> 00:00:55.000
new vocabulary as well.

20
00:00:55.000 --> 00:00:58.000
And speaking of vocabulary, remember you can download all the new words

21
00:00:58.000 --> 00:01:00.000
and phrases from this program.

22
00:01:00.000 --> 00:01:04.000
Plus, worksheet exercises to help you learn them on our website.

23
00:01:04.000 --> 00:01:06.000
BBCLearningEnglish.com

24
00:01:06.000 --> 00:01:08.000
Great.

25
00:01:08.000 --> 00:01:11.000
But first, I have a question for you, Phil.

26
00:01:11.000 --> 00:01:15.000
I mentioned that over half the human body consists of water.

27
00:01:15.000 --> 00:01:19.000
But there's an even higher percentage of water in our blood.

28
00:01:19.000 --> 00:01:25.000
But how much is our blood A around 80% water?

29
00:01:25.000 --> 00:01:28.000
B around 90% water?

30
00:01:28.000 --> 00:01:31.000
Or C 100% water?

31
00:01:31.000 --> 00:01:34.000
I think it's around 80% water.

32
00:01:34.000 --> 00:01:38.000
Okay, I will reveal the correct answer later in the program.

33
00:01:38.000 --> 00:01:44.000
Our blood needs water, so it can carry nutrients to the body's cells and organs.

34
00:01:44.000 --> 00:01:48.000
The amount recommended is often given as two liters a day.

35
00:01:48.000 --> 00:01:49.000
But why?

36
00:01:49.000 --> 00:01:54.000
Here to discuss this with BBC World Service Program, the Food Chain, is biologist,

37
00:01:54.000 --> 00:01:56.000
Professor John Speekman.

38
00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:01.000
So I'm not sure how it was arrived at, but it seems to be a number that has taken

39
00:02:01.000 --> 00:02:03.000
great on a very large number of countries.

40
00:02:03.000 --> 00:02:08.000
So if you look at government recommendations around the world, they pretty much all the same.

41
00:02:08.000 --> 00:02:13.000
They pretty much all say, everybody's got to be drinking two liters of water.

42
00:02:13.000 --> 00:02:19.000
Professor Speekman doesn't know how the number of two liters a day was arrived at.

43
00:02:19.000 --> 00:02:22.000
How it was decided or calculated.

44
00:02:22.000 --> 00:02:29.000
Nevertheless, the idea of drinking two liters a day has taken grip on many governments around the world.

45
00:02:29.000 --> 00:02:35.000
When you say an idea has taken grip on something, you mean it's taking control of it?

46
00:02:35.000 --> 00:02:42.000
Yes, Professor Speekman says that pretty much all governments are giving pretty much the same recommendation.

47
00:02:42.000 --> 00:02:46.000
He uses the phrase pretty much to mean almost.

48
00:02:46.000 --> 00:02:54.000
For example, pretty much all governments advised drinking two liters a day means almost all governments advise it.

49
00:02:54.000 --> 00:03:00.000
What Professor Speekman doesn't have, however, is any scientific evidence for this advice.

50
00:03:00.000 --> 00:03:05.000
The number of exactly two liters isn't based on scientific fact.

51
00:03:05.000 --> 00:03:07.000
It's more of a ballpark figure.

52
00:03:07.000 --> 00:03:12.000
A number which is a guess, but which you still believe is approximately correct.

53
00:03:12.000 --> 00:03:17.000
Actually, the amount of water in our bodies is changing all the time.

54
00:03:17.000 --> 00:03:23.000
Like your bank balance, which goes down when you spend money, your body loses water all the time

55
00:03:23.000 --> 00:03:26.000
When you breathe, sweat or go to the toilet.

56
00:03:26.000 --> 00:03:32.000
Exactly how much you need to drink depends on how much water your body needs to replace.

57
00:03:32.000 --> 00:03:34.000
And that may lead depends on your size.

58
00:03:34.000 --> 00:03:38.000
But what happens when we drink less than we should?

59
00:03:38.000 --> 00:03:47.000
It is hydration expert, Dr. Nidia Rodriguez Sanchez describing the effects of dehydration to BBC World Services, the Food Chain.

60
00:03:47.000 --> 00:03:53.000
And also many times we start getting dehydrated and we don't realize we are the hydrated.

61
00:03:53.000 --> 00:04:02.000
So it's very common that we feel tired or we feel like we're having a headache or even we think we are hungry.

62
00:04:02.000 --> 00:04:06.000
So we're going to get some food and actually what is happening is that we are thirsty, that we are dehydrated.

63
00:04:06.000 --> 00:04:11.000
What is starting to show some signs or some symptoms of dehydration?

64
00:04:11.000 --> 00:04:15.000
Dr. Sanchez describes the effect of dehydration.

65
00:04:15.000 --> 00:04:21.000
The condition of not having enough water in your body so that you feel ill or weak.

66
00:04:21.000 --> 00:04:28.000
She mentions feeling tired, having a headache or a dry mouth as symptoms of dehydration.

67
00:04:28.000 --> 00:04:34.000
Simsams are signs or feelings in the body showing the presence of some illness or condition.

68
00:04:34.000 --> 00:04:45.000
So whether you drink a little more or a little less, it seems that around two liters of water a day is a good way to keep your blood and body healthy.

69
00:04:45.000 --> 00:04:49.000
Speaking of which, Phil, it's time to reveal the answer to my question.

70
00:04:49.000 --> 00:05:02.000
What percentage of our blood is water? You said 80% and the answer is 90% our blood consists of around 90% water.

71
00:05:02.000 --> 00:05:12.000
Okay, let's recap the vocabulary we've used starting with the phrase to arrive at a number, meaning to decide it by doing calculations.

72
00:05:12.000 --> 00:05:17.000
If an idea takes grip on something, it takes control of it.

73
00:05:17.000 --> 00:05:27.000
The phrase pretty much means almost. For example, pretty much everyone likes chocolates, which means almost everyone likes chocolate.

74
00:05:27.000 --> 00:05:34.000
A ballpark figure is a phrase meaning a number which is an acceptable accurate approximation.

75
00:05:34.000 --> 00:05:41.000
dehydration is the condition of not having enough water in your body so that you feel ill or weak.

76
00:05:41.000 --> 00:05:49.000
And finally, a symptom is a sign or feeling in the body showing the presence of an illness or condition.

77
00:05:49.000 --> 00:05:58.000
Once again, our six minutes are up. Why not join me now and head over to our website, BBCLearningEnglish.com.

78
